page.text: The site plan for this parcel proposes one full-movement access and one right-in/right-out access
on Holly Springs Road. The proposed full-movement access will provide a fourth leg to the Holly
Springs Road and Cary Parkway intersection. This traffic study, 14-TAR-379, analyzes the
effects of the proposed Pritchett Property development on traffic operations in the study area.
Figure ES-1 shows the study area for 14-TAR-379 while Figure ES-2 provides the site plan.
The number of trips generated by the Pritchett Property development will exceed the Town’s 100
peak hour trip threshold for development (Land Development Ordinance (LDO), Section 3.4.1)
and therefore will require a Traffic Analysis Report (TAR). This property is also located inside the
Town of Cary’s “Base Benefit Transportation Zone” as identified in the Town’s LDO Section
7.11.6. The projected build-out year for this development is 2017. This TAR analyzes the
potential impacts of the proposed development on the adjacent roadways and offers potential
improvements for those impacts as necessary.

This section of the TAR describes the existing roadways within the study area.
Walnut Street is a major north-south thoroughfare that serves numerous land uses in the
Town of Cary. Walnut Street runs from Kildaire Farm Road in downtown Cary on the
north end to Tryon Road on the south end where it becomes Holly Springs Road. Walnut
Street provides access to US 1/US 64 in southwestern Wake County as well as the
Crossroads and Centrum shopping centers, multiple residences, Cary Towne Center, and
downtown Cary. The typical section of Walnut Street within the study area is a median-
divided six-lane roadway and has a posted speed limit of 45 mph. Walnut Street had a
2011 AADT (annual average daily traffic) ranging from 19,000 vehicles per day in
between Macedonia Road and Dillard Drive to 29,000 vehicles per day just north of
Dillard Drive (based on 2011 NCDOT traffic volume GIS data).
Walnut Street changes names to Holly Springs Road south of its intersection with Tryon
Road. Holly Springs Road continues as a north-south connector that runs from the Tryon
Road intersection to NC 55 in Holly Springs. The typical section of Holly Springs Road
within the study area is a two-lane undivided roadway south of Jones Franklin Road that
widens to a divided roadway with three northbound lanes and two southbound lanes
between Jones Franklin Road and Tryon Road.
Transportation Plan (CTP) identifies the vision to widen Holly Springs Road to a four-lane
median-divided facility in the future. Holly Springs Road has a posted speed limit of 45
mph within the study limits. Holly Springs Road had a 2011 AADT ranging from 14,000
vehicles per day in between Tryon Road and Jones Franklin Road to 21,000 vehicles per
day south of Jones Franklin Road (based on 2011 NCDOT traffic volume GIS data).
Tryon Road is a major east-west connector that serves numerous land uses from
business to retail to residential. Tryon Road begins at the US 1 and US 64 interchange
and ends in Garner, NC at Garner Road. The typical section of Tryon Road within the
study area limits is a median-divided four-lane roadway and it has a posted speed limit of
45 mph. Tryon Road had a 2011 AADT ranging from 17,000 vehicles per day just west of
the study limits to 28,000 vehicles per day just east of the study limits (based on 2011
Jones Franklin Road is a major north-south connector that runs from Hillsborough Street
in Raleigh to Holly Springs Road in Cary. Jones Franklin Road also forms a partial
cloverleaf interchange with I-440 and US 1 north of the study area. The typical section of
Jones Franklin Road within the study limits is a two-lane undivided roadway. Jones
Franklin Road had 2011 AADTs of 8,100 vehicles per day between Holly Springs Road
and Tryon Road, 11,000 vehicles per day between Tryon Road and Macedonia Road,
and 9,800 vehicles per day north of Macedonia Road (based on 2011 NCDOT traffic
Cary Parkway is a major connector that runs from Harrison Avenue in northern Cary to
Holly Springs Road in southeastern Cary, providing a partial loop around western Cary
and serving multiple land uses. The typical section of Cary Parkway in the study area is a
four-lane median-divided roadway. Cary Parkway has a posted speed limit of 45 mph.
Cary Parkway had a 2011 AADT of 9,400 vehicles per day just west of the study limits
(based on 2011 NCDOT traffic volume GIS data).

Drive which currently ends just south of the
site’s property line. Fordland Drive does not connect
to Holly Springs Road but does provide an indirect connection to Holly Springs Road via

accessing Tryon Road by way of Holly Springs Road would be a much shorter trip for site traffic.
Therefore, this TAR has no site traffic routed along Fordland Drive.
It is anticipated that some existing traffic may use Fordland Drive to access the signalized
intersection of Holly Springs Road and Cary Parkway/Proposed Access 1 and vice-versa;
therefore, the number of existing trips originating along Fordland Drive and Campbell Road was
estimated based upon aerial photography and ITE Trip Generation. It was assumed that these
estimated trips currently access Holly Springs Road via the unsignalized intersection of Campbell
Road and Holly Springs Road. For the Background (2017) and Combined (2017) analyses, a
portion of these estimated trips were rerouted to Fordland Drive, resulting in volume
modifications at the Holly Springs Road and Cary Parkway/Proposed Access 1 intersection. This
traffic volume estimation and corresponding distribution calculations are located in Appendix D.

It should be noted that the initial Synchro analyses for the Combined (2017) scenario resulted
all signalized intersections operating at LOS D or better in the AM and PM peak periods;
however, the westbound right-turn at Proposed Access 2 operates at LOS F with
unreasonably high delay, indicating congestion along northbound Holly Springs Road. Given
these results, the SimTraffic simulation was observed in order to verify and observe this
congestion. During the simulation of the AM peak period, northbound queues on Jones
Franklin Road extended from the Tryon Road intersection south beyond the Holly Springs
Road and Jones Franklin Road intersection. It is reasonable to assume that if northbound
queues on Jones Franklin road reach the Holly Springs Road intersection, a portion of that
traffic may choose to continue straight on Holly Springs Road and make a right-turn at the
Holly Springs Road and Tryon Road intersection to reach the intersection of Tryon Road and
Jones Franklin Road. Using this rationale, a portion of the northbound trips on Holly Springs
Road destined for eastbound Tryon Road and northbound Jones Franklin Road were
rerouted to the intersection of Holly Springs Road and Tryon Road based on engineering
judgment. The simulation was then observed again and found to be more reasonable with
the rerouted traffic. In order to estimate the average delay for the westbound right-turns at
Proposed Access 2 during the AM peak period, ten simulation runs were performed. After
compiling ten simulation runs with this rerouted traffic in the Combined (2017) AM peak
scenario, SimTraffic indicates that the average delay will be below the threshold for LOS D. It
should also be noted that the average delay reported in SimTraffic does not directly coincide
with the control delay as described in the Highway Capacity Manual for determining level of
service because it is calculated over the entire 60 minute analysis period, rather than the
peak 15 minutes. The Jones Franklin Road volume reroute calculations are provided in
Appendix D. The Synchro results and SimTraffic results without the Jones Franklin Road
traffic reroutes are provided in Appendix H.
